Joan Baez and the Byrds."}],"references":["47a4810a-8469-4549-997e-9a92413c936b_297787233","0358c543-d6f0-4045-a6b0-e5af2d1d9c23_1070844357","a7d27d37-430a-421c-970a-fc3f881154f1_254411131"],"documents":{"a7d27d37-430a-421c-970a-fc3f881154f1_254411131":{"id":"a7d27d37-430a-421c-970a-fc3f881154f1_254411131","text":"Had an ol\u2019 dog his name was Blue, betcha five dollars he\u2019s good dog too\u201d American folk song \u201cOld Blue\u201d\n\nMost of us have known a dog named Blue at some time in our life. Maybe you were lucky and owned one yourself. From reading these pages you know that I have had a lot of dogs in my time (too many) but in truth I never had one named Blue. I did own a beautiful Bluetick coonhound back in the day who could have easily been called Blue, but at my Dad\u2019s behest he was named Lead, as in you would lead a dog on a leash. (That was a popular hound name at one time I think) Anyhow, Blue has always been a name given to hunting dogs.\n\nThe song I quoted back there is an old folk song done back in the minstrel show days and went on to become popular and was recorded by of all people Joan Baez and the Byrds. Hounds and other hunting dogs are part of our American history and culture, no matter how much some of us don\u2019t want to recognize it. Sadly there are some out there today who because they say they don\u2019t like hunting; they want this part of our past erased and unrecognized. Well, it is there, it is a part of us, and those of us who are hunters are proud of it and want it preserved, but that may be a sermon for another time.\n\nThose who know me know I love all hunting dogs, from bony pointers to block headed Labradors, to fiesty Cur dogs and bawl mouthed hound dogs. (\u201cBawl\u201d is a type of bark that a hound often does, just stay with me here, we will educate you about this huntin\u2019 dog world.) The topic I want to touch on here for a minute is that in the outdoor industry media and print world, bird dogs like pointers and setters and spaniels, along with the retriever breeds like the hugely popular Labrador are usually talked about a lot more than hounds and Curs and other dogs that are considered \u201ctree\u201d dogs. (Tree dogs are hunting dogs that pursue game be it bears, squirrels, or raccoons and bark at the tree till the hunter gets there)\n\nRecently I am seeing what I hope is a renaissance in this area in that the lesser known hound breeds like Blueticks, Plotts, and Walkers, along with the many varieties of Cur and Fiest dogs are coming in from the cold and may get more press and recognition. Why do I say this? So glad you asked!\n\nI few days ago I had the pleasure of joining Ben Sheets on his podcast \u201cTree Talkin\u2019 Time\u201d which can be found on Apple, Libsyn, Spotify, and other podcast destinations. Ben hails from Pennsylvania and is \u201ceat up\u201d with the whole treed dog and hound world and it shows in the passion he relates in his podcast.\n\n\u201cI have been involved with tree dogs for the past 15 years and got my start with curs and fiest while in college.\u201d Ben said. \u201cI squirrel hunted during the day and coon hunted at night. After graduation and moving home I transitioned to primarily coon hunting because of time constraints. When I made this shift, I got a few American Leopard Hounds. Through them I was able to meet some bear hunters and I was able to go on my first bear hunt, and I\u2019ve been hooked ever since.\n\nI live in Pennsylvania where it\u2019s not legal to pursue bears with hounds and have to travel to Virginia and West Virginia to do so. I didn\u2019t grow up hunting and while I enjoy it, the dogs and the work they do is why I am drawn to this lifestyle.\u201d\n\n(Ben told me if it were ossible he would move to West Virginia so he could run bear hounds all the time!) Do your self a favor and check out his podcast. https://treetalkintime.libsyn.com\n\nAnother bright spot that I see has appeared in the print world of outdoor media. I was honored and humbled to have an article on Cur dogs appear in the first issue of Hound magazine a new addition in the lineup for Game and Fish magazines in the publishing house of the Outdoor Sportsmans Group (OSG). This is a nicely done, full color magazine with beautiful photography and content from some well-known writers in the hunting related media world. (Even if they did have me in this issue)\n\nDog men and women out there also know that very soon the revered tree dog magazine Full Cry is making a comeback under the new management of Dani and Jason Duby from Oregon.\n\nThey are bringing back a publication that has been around since the 1930\u2019s and has been the mainstay for those in the hound, squirrel dog, and coonhound world. Many of your Dads and Grandads will tell you about reading Full Cry since they were kids. I think you will see a new, revamped, and attractive version of Full Cry while at the same time you will get the hound and tree dog news like you remember. I am excited to see this and so happy the Duby household took on this mammoth task of keeping Full Cry in print. www.fullcrymag.com\n\nMaybe the sad eyed hound and the fiesty squirrel dog will be getting a little more respect.\n\nI hope so, Ol\u2019 Blue has been waiting a long time.\n\nTrending Video\n\nRecommended for you","url":"https://www.bdtonline.com/sports/old-blue-moves-uptown-with-magazine-for-owners-of-hunting-hounds/article_b37e1f80-46ca-11ee-85c3-970588f0fa57.html"},"47a4810a-8469-4549-997e-9a92413c936b_297787233":{"id":"47a4810a-8469-4549-997e-9a92413c936b_297787233","text":"Home Lifestyle Have Healthier Lifestyle \u2013 Things To Look Out For When Choosing A New Bicycle\n\nHave Healthier Lifestyle \u2013 Things To Look Out For When Choosing A New Bicycle\n\n4\u00a0min read\n0\n\nWhen it comes to choosing the right bicycle, it cannot be easy because of the many options that you have, but the first thing you need to know is where you will be cycling; when you know this, you will be able to choose the right bicycle for yourself.\u00a0 In case you are not of an age where you can make the right choice for yourself, your parents must know where you will be cycling so that they can get you the right bicycle. Moreover, it would help if you remembered that there are so many bicycles out there, and every person has a different need for cycling.\u00a0\n\nFirst, you need to know what you want, like do you want to do tricks, race, or do something fast. When you know all these things, you will be able to buy the right bike for yourself (more info).\u00a0 Also, before you buy your bicycle, ask yourself questions like how long you will stay with your bike and when you know this, you will be able to buy the right bicycle to fit your needs.\u00a0\n\nSome of the things you need to consider before you buy your bicycle include;\n\n  1. Learn how to ride a bike\u00a0\n\nBefore buying a bike, you should ask yourself questions like do I know how to ride a bike? If not, you should start on a basic single-speed bike with coaster brakes. These bikes are great because you don\u2019t have to worry about shifting gears and front/ rear braking sequences. When you start with this bike, you will be able to learn how to ride a bike faster than starting with a complex bike.\n\n  1. Learn about the basic types of bikes\u00a0\n\nThere are so many types of bikes you can choose from, and each bike offers different capabilities. It would help if you also bought a bike that fits the area you live in or where you will be cycling. If you live in the city, the best bike to buy is a bike built for roads, and when you live in a place where you can bike on trails, then a mountain bike would be the right option for you.\u00a0\n\n  1. Decide between quality and costs\u00a0\n\nWhen searching for a bicycle, you have so many options to choose from depending on the amount of money you have, says Wikihow. When it comes to road bikes, they are better for commuting and speed, but they can be a bit expensive, mainly when it comes to the material and quality of the road bike you have decided to buy, according to LifeHacker. For bikes like cruiser and hybrid bikes, they offer you enough room to add your accessories.\u00a0\n\n  1. Know the type of terrain you will be biking on\u00a0\n\nMost road and mountain bikes have gears and shifters, usually operated by some trigger. When biking on hilly terrain, the best bike is one that shifts gears. Regarding fixie bikes, they don\u2019t have shifters, and they are usually lighter, faster and great for flat commutes. But for this type of bike, you need to have the right skills so that you can be able to ride it appropriately.\u00a0\u00a0\n\n  1. Parts and accessories\u00a0\n\nThe moment you have chosen the bike you want, it\u2019s time to focus on the parts and accessories that will come with your bike. Most bikes are sold with the parts needed for the bike and nothing else. If you want anything added to your bike, it\u2019s you to choose what you want, and some of the things you can add to your bike are cages for water bottles, lights, pumps, locks, cycle computers and pedals.\u00a0\n\n  1. Sizing up\u00a0\n\nWhen cycling, you want to be comfortable and to attain this, you will have to get a bike that is the right size. The good thing about bikes is that they come in four or five different sizes, making it easy to choose the right bike that fits you. An uncomfortable bike can make it uncomfortable for you as you cycle. Choosing the right size depends on factors like height, inseam length, riding experience and flexibility. When all these factors have been considered, and you have found the right bike, the next step is ensuring your saddle has been adjusted and fitted correctly.\u00a0\n\n  1. Know where to buy your bike from\u00a0\n\nKnowing the type of activity you will be doing with your bike will make it easy for you to determine the shop you will go to. If you think of regular cycling, the best store for you is a specialist bike store or an online bike shop but be very careful when shopping from an online store.\u00a0\n\nConclusion\n\nWhen buying a bike, you won\u2019t be faced with its appearance and colour only because so many things need to be considered to get the right bike for yourself.\u00a0\n\nLast Updated: September 9, 2022\n\nCheck Also\n\nThe Best Portable External Monitors\n\nAll laptops come with an integrated screen for the buyers and provide a good display. Howe\u2026","url":"https://www.criticalhit.net/lifestyle/have-healthier-lifestyle-things-to-look-out-for-when-choosing-a-new-bicycle/"},"0358c543-d6f0-4045-a6b0-e5af2d1d9c23_1070844357":{"id":"0358c543-d6f0-4045-a6b0-e5af2d1d9c23_1070844357","text":"Press \"Enter\" to skip to content\n\nHow to Choose the Right Bank for Your Small Business\n\nHow to Choose the Right Bank for Your Small Business \u2013 As a small business owner, you want to make sure that you\u2019re getting the most out of your bank and receiving the best possible service for your needs. If you\u2019re unhappy with your current bank, it may be time to look at other options out there. With so many options available, choosing the right bank can be difficult, but if you know what to look for in a small business bank, you can find one that fits your business just right.\n\nStep 1: List Down Features You Need\n\nThe first step is to list down the features you need from a bank. Do you need a bank that offers loans? Or one that has a lot of experience working with small businesses? Maybe you need a bank with good customer service or one with physical locations near you. Whatever your needs are, make sure to write them down.\n\nStep 2: Identify Five Banks You Can Work With\n\nThe next step is to identify five banks you can work with. This may seem like a daunting task, but it\u2019s important to do your research and find banks that fit your needs. To help get started, you might try using this handy list of questions:\nFrequently Asked Questions about Banking\nHow much does it cost?\nWhat kinds of services are offered?\nWhat kind of deposit minimums are required?\nCan I access my account online?\nCan I bank on my phone or tablet?\n\nSee also\u00a0 Personal Loan vs. Auto Loan \u2014 Which is Better for Financing a Car\n\nHow secure is my information when I\u2019m banking online or on mobile devices?\n\nStep 3: Determine What Features They Have in Common\n\nThe first step is to make a list of all the features you want in a bank. Do you want online banking? Mobile banking? In-person support? Once you have your list, you can start narrowing down your options by finding banks that have all or most of the features on your list. If there are some important features missing from their website, don\u2019t be afraid to call them and ask if they offer those services. It\u2019s important not to get too hung up on one feature over another because you will always be able to find some way of accessing your money no matter what type of bank you choose.\n\nStep 4: Narrow Down to Two-Three Banks\n\nResearching and narrowing down your options is critical when choosing a bank for your small business. You want to find a bank that offers the best combination of features, fees, and customer service. To do this, start by making a list of your top three banks. Then, read online reviews and compare fees. Finally, talk to other small business owners to get their recommendations. By taking these steps, you\u2019ll be able to choose the right bank for your small business.\n\nStep 5: Meet Them In Person and Apply\n\nYou\u2019ve finally narrowed your choices down to a few banks. Now it\u2019s time to set up appointments and meet with each one. This is an important step in choosing the right bank for your small business. You want to get a feel for the people you\u2019ll be working with and make sure they understand your business.\n\nSee also\u00a0 Africans in Diaspora Remit $40b yearly\u2019\n\nStep 6: Analyze the Application Approval Process\n\nThe process of applying for and being approved for a small business loan can be time-consuming and stressful. But it doesn\u2019t have to be! Here are a few tips on how to choose the right bank for your small business:\n1. Do your research. Compare rates, terms, and conditions from multiple lenders.\n2. Consider online lenders. Many online lenders offer fast approvals and funding.\n3. Read the fine print. A lender\u2019s interest rate may not include an origination fee or other additional charges that can quickly add up. Some banks also charge a monthly fee regardless of whether you use the account or not.\n4. Beware hidden fees. Other charges such as cashier\u2019s checks, wire transfers, or overdraft protection may come with their own set of fees in addition to those charged by the lender and those incurred by your business in general (e.g., credit card processing fees).\n\nStep 7: Decide on the Best Bank For You\n\nChoosing the right bank is a critical step for any small business owner. The wrong bank can cost you time and money, so it\u2019s important to do your research and choose carefully. You\u2019ll want to select a bank that offers the services you need at an affordable price. For example, if you need help with marketing strategies or company management, make sure your chosen bank offers those services before signing up. You may also want to consider how close the nearest branch is or how easy it will be for employees in different locations to deposit their checks into their accounts each month.\n\nYou cannot copy content of this page","url":"https://businessfinancedaily.com/2022/07/09/how-to-choose-the-right-bank-for-your-small-business/"}}}
