 4 election\n\nJamie Rokus\nWisconsin Rapids Daily Tribune\n\nIncumbent Sheri Evanson will face challenger Jake Cattanach for the District 5 seat on the Wisconsin Rapids City Council in the April 4 election.\n\nAlderpersons serve a two-year term.\n\nTo learn more about registering to vote and to find your polling place, visit\u00a0My Vote Wisconsin.\n\nThe Wisconsin Rapids Daily Tribune asked each of the candidates to address important issues in the district and why they are running for the position.\n\nJake Cattanach\n\nAge: 32\n\nResidence: Wisconsin Rapids\n\nOccupation and education: Entrepreneur; associate degree in business administration\n\nRelevant experience: I served two terms as alderman until vacating the seat due to the redistricting of the city. During that time I served on the Public Works, Finance and Property committee as secretary.\n\nCampaign website/Facebook page: Vote for Jake Cattanach on Facebook or email Vote4JakeCattanach@gmail.com\n\nSheri Evanson\n\nAge: 53\n\nResidence: Wisconsin Rapids\n\nOccupation and education: Deputy county clerk for Wood County; associate degrees in supervisory management and business administration\n\nRelevant experience: I am honored to have been elected to serve the citizens as the District 5 alderperson for the past two years. Working with the other alderpersons, mayor, city staff and the citizens who we serve, has been an invaluable experience. Having the knowledge and ambition to conduct research, ask questions, investigate and listen has helped me succeed in this position. Working in my current position at the county the last 18 years as well as my prior work with the state of Wisconsin for five years continues to provide me with skills and proficiency.\n\nCampaign website/Facebook page:Alderperson District Five \u2013 City of Wisconsin Rapids on Facebook\n\nWhy are you running for this position?\n\nCattanach: I want to see the city on a successful path now and in the future. I\u2019m a lifelong resident heavily invested in the community and raising a family here. Residents have reached out and asked me to be their voice in the Council chambers during a time of change from what we\u2019ve known to what we will be. It's important to have strong leadership during such times, and I believe I can contribute to that.\n\nEvanson: I am running as the alderperson of District 5 because I feel what happens within this city directly affects each and every citizen. Listening to the citizens and understanding their vision and the direction in which they believe the city should be today, tomorrow and the future is vital to the city\u2019s existence. Helping the city become sustainable financially and socially, jobs, infrastructure, recreation and housing are all vital to the growth of Wisconsin Rapids. Submitting a fiscally responsible budget while trying to increase and maintain infrastructure as well as keeping taxes fair is a very complicated but important task.\n\nWhat are residents telling you are the most important issues in District 5, and how would you address them?\n\nCattanach: The residents want to be heard and informed. District 5 is home to citizens of all walks of life with many different views on what\u2019s important in the city. They often feel like they\u2019re unaware of decisions being made in the city. I will strive to inform them on what\u2019s going on in their local government and be their voice. I will be available via all forms of communication to hear everyone's concerns and questions while leaving any partisan politics at the door.\n\nEvanson: Questions are always different according to what decisions the city makes. The most important issue I am hearing lately is the amount of garbage and junk lying about at homes. Houses and properties that are rundown and probably not compliant are a top concern for my constituents. In this instance, I advise citizens to use the SeeClickFix app to report problems, which go directly to the code enforcement officer. If there are recurring issues, I reach out to the code enforcement officer/police/staff to investigate and get resolution. Road conditions are also a top priority among citizens.\n\nWhat are the top two issues that you believe the Council should address?\n\nCattanach: The top two issues that need to be addressed are the ones the citizens inquire about the most, the reconstruction of the roads and the paper mill. We need answers as to what\u2019s going on with the paper mill and what the future is for the Verso property. The elected officials of the city cannot let this fall on the back burner no matter how much time passes. We need to continue to apply pressure to see a sale of the mill or repurpose of the property. I believe we can make progress toward this through policy and legal means.\n\nEvanson: To continue to incorporate a fiscally responsible budget, I would like the Council to address avenues in which the city could increase revenues to help alleviate some debt and expenses the citizens of Wisconsin Rapids incur. Collaboration with surrounding municipalities is vital, however, our citizens should not bear more expense for shared resources. Another issue is to continually monitor road conditions. Thankfully, a portion of Eighth Street is on the schedule for 2028, but we as a Council are hopeful our outreach to county and state representatives could urge the state for a quicker start date.\n\nThe city has been discussing issues with blocked train crossings for years and recently received a \u201cFeasibility Study Report.\u201d How would you like to see the city address this issue?\n\nCattanach: The \u201cFeasibility Study Report'' provided similar data to the multiple studies that have been done on the city railroad crossings over the years. These \u201cstudies'' are costing city taxpayers money to tell us what we already know. The funds for the studies should be repurposed to actually solving the railroad crossing issues. This can be done cost effectively by utilizing modern technology to provide citizens with live information on train schedules, train wait time, alternate routes and other information that can assist them in their daily commute.\n\nEvanson: A bittersweet topic due to the mill closure and reduction in local fracking, train traffic has substantially been reduced. However, there continues to be congestion with rail traffic within the city. The \"Feasibility Study\" recently acquired will be dissected and discussed at the Public Works meeting, a special and regular council meeting in March. With the financial cost consideration, I would at least like the city to incorporate a mobility system that citizens could pull up on an app and find out where/when rail traffic will be present. I would also encourage the city to develop quiet zone area improvements.\n\nSince the closure of the Verso mill in 2020, residents have been discussing the need for more businesses and manufacturing jobs in the city. How can the City Council play a role in attracting new businesses?\n\nCattanach: The Council needs to make the message clear to entrepreneurs and companies looking for a home and that message is \u201cWe\u2019re open for business.\" We need to adjust our policies to make this an attractive place to start or expand a business. I would propose the city create a position in the Community Development department that is related strictly to economic development. This would provide entrepreneurs and companies with someone to assist them in growing in Wisconsin Rapids and navigating through any barriers to entry.\n\nEvanson: I believe the city needs to encourage and develop more manufacturing growth within the city. Tax breaks and reduced infrastructure costs could play a huge role in enticing businesses. In collaboration with an eligible workforce, affordable housing, child care options and recreational opportunities, new business growth could succeed. I believe the city needs to have attractive business fronts and a good working plan consisting of the mayor, community development and the Council. The Rapids Rediscovered Program is a good start to encourage housing that is more attractive. The Council needs to continue working with staff to ensure grant opportunities are utilized.\n\nMore:These 4 retailers will move into the former Wisconsin Rapids Shopko. Here's what they'll offer.\n\nMore:Wisconsin Rapids development projects to watch in 2023: Shopko building, hospital, jail\n\nEditor Jamie Rokus can be reached at jrokus@gannett.com or follow her on Twitter at @Jamie_Rokus.","url":"https://www.wisconsinrapidstribune.com/story/news/politics/elections/2023/03/16/wisconsin-rapids-city-council-district-5-candidates-on-spring-2023-ballot/69982622007/"},"509f3201-aca2-4757-9474-c669107d4717_419992755":{"id":"509f3201-aca2-4757-9474-c669107d4717_419992755","text":"What does tire monitor fault mean?\n\nIntroduction\n\nModern vehicles are equipped with various safety features that help provide a smooth and secure driving experience. One such feature is the tire pressure monitoring system (TPMS), which helps drivers monitor the air pressure in their tires. However, sometimes we may encounter a tire monitor fault message on our dashboard, leaving us wondering what it means and what actions we should take.\n\nWhat does tire monitor fault mean?\n\nTire monitor fault means that there is an issue with the tire pressure monitoring system in your vehicle. This warning typically appears on your dashboard and indicates that the system is unable to communicate with one or more tire sensors. The fault could be due to a malfunctioning sensor or a problem with the system itself.\n\nRelated FAQs\n\n1. How does the tire pressure monitoring system work?\n\nThe TPMS utilizes sensors in each tire to monitor the air pressure. It transmits the data wirelessly to the vehicle\u2019s computer system, which then notifies the driver if the tire pressure is too low or high.\n\n2. Why is TPMS important?\n\nMaintaining proper tire pressure is crucial for safety and performance. TPMS helps prevent premature tire wear, improves fuel efficiency, and reduces the risk of tire blowouts.\n\n3. What causes a tire monitor fault?\n\nA tire monitor fault can be caused by a faulty sensor, low sensor battery, damaged wiring, or a problem with the TPMS control module.\n\n4. Can I continue driving with a tire monitor fault?\n\nWhile you can drive with a tire monitor fault, it is not advisable. Without a functioning TPMS, you won\u2019t be alerted to potential tire pressure issues, increasing the risk of accidents or tire damage.\n\n5. How can I fix a tire monitor fault?\n\nTo fix a tire monitor fault, you should first check all the tire pressures manually. If they are within the recommended range, the fault might be due to a faulty sensor or other system-related issues, in which case it is recommended to visit a qualified mechanic.\n\n6. How much does it cost to repair a tire monitor fault?\n\nThe cost to repair a tire monitor fault depends on the cause and the vehicle. It is recommended to consult with a professional technician to determine the exact cost.\n\n7. Can I reset the TPMS myself?\n\nIn some cases, you can manually reset the TPMS by following the instructions in your vehicle\u2019s manual. However, if the fault persists, it is advisable to seek professional assistance.\n\n8. Are tire monitor faults covered under warranty?\n\nIf your vehicle is still under warranty, tire monitor faults may be covered depending on the terms and conditions of the warranty. It is best to consult with your vehicle manufacturer or authorized dealer for specific details.\n\n9. How often should I check my tire pressure?\n\nEven with a functioning TPMS, it is still recommended to manually check your tire pressure every month or before long trips. TPMS is not foolproof, and manual checks ensure accurate readings.\n\n10. Can extreme temperatures affect the TPMS?\n\nExtreme temperatures can impact the TPMS sensors\u2019 accuracy. In cold weather, tire pressure may decrease, triggering false alerts. Conversely, in hot weather, tire pressure may increase, leading to potential issues that may not be detected by the TPMS.\n\n11. How long do TPMS sensors last?\n\nTPMS sensors typically have a battery life of 5-7 years. However, their lifespan can vary based on factors like usage, climate, and maintenance.\n\n12. Are aftermarket TPMS sensors reliable?\n\nAftermarket TPMS sensors can vary in quality and reliability. It is recommended to choose sensors from reputable brands and ensure they are compatible with your vehicle\u2019s TPMS system. Seeking professional advice is always a good idea.\n\nConclusion\n\nUnderstanding what a tire monitor fault means and taking appropriate action is vital for maintaining safe driving conditions. If you encounter a tire monitor fault warning on your dashboard, it is advisable to have the issue diagnosed and repaired promptly by a qualified mechanic. Remember to regularly check your tire pressure, even when the TPMS is functioning correctly, to ensure optimal performance and safety on the road.\n\nScroll to Top","url":"https://epn.org/what-does-tire-monitor-fault-mean/"},"b3b0382a-c38c-4858-8b00-38e921fd7e35_125800405":{"id":"b3b0382a-c38c-4858-8b00-38e921fd7e35_125800405","text":"Successfully reported this slideshow.\nWe use your LinkedIn profile and activity data to personalize ads and to show you more relevant ads. You can change your ad preferences anytime.\nUpcoming SlideShare\nWhat to Upload to SlideShare\nLoading in \u20263\n\u00d7\n1 of 3\n\nTop 10 benefits of professional carpet cleaning - mulgoa\n\n0\n\nShare\n\nDownload to read offline\n\nCarpet cleaning is crucial but it\u2019s not the most exciting of chores in the home. It\u2019s something we must all be thinking about and prioritizing. It\u2019s one of those tasks we tend to put off because it appears like a daunting task however it\u2019s definitely worth thinking about. In addition to